flowchart LR

  subgraph INTENT["1. Path objective"]
    G1["Turn runtime event history into durably preserved, immutable archive history that later replay, audit, and learning can trust"]
    G2["Keep this path narrower than append-only audit truth and narrower than later replay-basis closure for learning input"]
    G3["Answer where the platform preserves runtime events as immutable archive history and refs"]
  end

  subgraph ENTRY["2. Entry basis"]
    E1["The system-design entry is current-run runtime event history that the archive lane is responsible for preserving"]
    E2["The cutover proof entry for validation was narrower: control-topic probe records as bounded continuity proof"]
    E3["So the system-design entry is runtime event history, while the cutover proof entry was a narrower probe source"]
  end

  subgraph SPINE["5. Broad route logic"]
    R1["Runtime or probe source records on MSK"]
    R2["Archive-consumer runtime"]
    R3["Object-storage archive prefix"]
    R4["Run-scoped archive objects with payload and readback continuity proof"]
    R5["Immutable archive history for replay and audit"]
  end

  subgraph CARRIES["4. What the path carries"]
    C1["Runtime records to be preserved"]
    C2["Run identity"]
    C3["Continuity metadata"]
    C4["Enough payload and readback information to prove that what landed in object storage is the right run-scoped archive history"]
    C5["The path also carries proof mode, source topic, starting-position rule, batch and window settings, and run-scope readback strategy"]
    C6["Later learning-input closure depends on archive plus replay references being resolved from spine closure, so archive history is retained for later causal replay as well as human inspection"]
  end

  subgraph LOGIC["6. Logical design reading"]
    L1["The platform treats immutable runtime history as different from both append-only audit truth and later replay-basis selection for learning"]
    L2["The system is not saying audit append is enough and replay can infer history later"]
    L3["There is a separate archive-preservation boundary whose job is to preserve immutable runtime history and refs in durable object storage"]
    L4["That separation is visible in the docs: the audit surface has one purpose, the archive writer has another, RTDL catch-up closure requires archive closure evidence, and later learning-input closure depends on archive plus replay references as input"]
    L5["That is strong A-level design signal"]
  end

  subgraph SEATING["7. Concrete seating in the current wired system"]
    S1["The copied baseline wired graphs show a live archive_writer deployment in the RTDL namespace"]
    S2["The archive writer writes immutable history to the archive prefix"]
    S3["The archive writer stores archive receipts in evidence"]
    S4["The durable archive substrate is object storage under archive/{platform_run_id}/events/"]
    S5["The current runtime handle set pins the archive connector mode, source cluster, source topic, batch/window controls, and run-scope proof mode"]
    S6["The live runtime truth shows the archive writer as concrete RTDL workload, and later bounded proof notes recorded the archive writer as green while the rest of RTDL diagnosis continued"]
    S7["That is strong A-style evidence that this path is materially present in the system, not only planned"]
  end

  subgraph RATIONALE["8. Why the design looks like this"]
    Y1["The platform wanted a managed, production-shaped archive sink with explicit continuity proof, but the exact runtime route had to be adjudicated through real constraints"]
    Y2["The lane tried Firehose with MSK source and then Lambda MSK event-source mapping"]
    Y3["Both hit real blocker classes or service/runtime constraints"]
    Y4["The lane then closed green after repinning the current mode to ECS batch-consumer to S3"]
    Y5["The objective did not change: preserve run-scoped archive sink semantics and continuity proof, but the concrete runtime route did"]
    Y6["So for A, the right story is that the current wired archive path is the adjudicated route that kept the semantic objective intact under real constraints"]
  end

  subgraph CONTRACT["9. What larger contracts are shaping this path"]
    X1["The design authority says the archive writer is part of the audit and archive runtime posture and must preserve replay and offset continuity proof"]
    X2["The run-process says RTDL catch-up closure cannot close without archive-writer closure evidence and archive closure marker"]
    X3["Later learning-input closure says learning input cannot begin until archive plus labels plus replay references are resolved from spine closure"]
    X4["So this path is shaped by archive preservation, closure evidence, and future replay-resolvability all at once"]
  end

  subgraph TRADEOFFS["10. Trade-offs and constraints"]
    T1["This path deliberately adds one more explicit truth boundary to the runtime side of the platform"]
    T2["That costs one more runtime consumer and sink lane, one more object-store continuity proof contract, and one more distinction the platform has to explain"]
    T3["It also forced uncomfortable but honest runtime choices"]
    T4["The lane did not declare green on Firehose because the MSK-source path was blocked, and it did not declare green on Lambda mapping when probe publication existed but no archive objects were produced"]
    T5["The lane stayed fail-closed until the current route could actually show probe-to-sink continuity"]
    T6["That is strong design signal because the archive boundary was treated as real rather than decorative"]
  end

  subgraph NECESSITY["11. Necessity test"]
    N1["If this path is removed, the platform can still ingest traffic, make decisions, emit actions, append audit truth, and even produce later governance bundles"]
    N2["But it loses a clean answer to where immutable runtime history is preserved"]
    N3["It loses a clean answer to what object-backed archive later replay should depend on"]
    N4["It loses a clean answer to how replay and offset continuity is grounded"]
    N5["It loses a clean answer to whether later learning input is built on actual archived runtime truth or inferred fragments"]
    N6["That would weaken A immediately because the system would have runtime behavior and audit append, but no explicit owner for the immutable event history that later replay and audit rely on"]
  end

  subgraph CLOSURE["3. Owned outcome and 12. What this path proves for A"]
    O1["Immutable archived event history under the platform's run-scoped archive surface"]
    O2["Continuity evidence exists that later consumers can resolve"]
    O3["The lane has enough continuity proof to claim that archive objects correspond to the source records it was responsible for preserving"]
    O4["Owned outcome: immutable archive history with run-scoped continuity proof"]
    A1["Purpose claim:<br/>the platform has a distinct job for preserving immutable runtime history for replay and audit"]
    A2["Intentionality claim:<br/>archive preservation is a named closure requirement with its own continuity proof, not an accidental object-store side effect"]
    A3["Materialization claim:<br/>the path is concretely seated in archive prefixes, pinned connector/runtime handles, and a live archive-writer workload"]
    A4["Contract claim:<br/>the path is governed by archive closure evidence, replay-reference expectations, and run-scope readback proof"]
    A5["Constraint-awareness claim:<br/>the current wired route is the result of fail-closed runtime adjudication across multiple attempted sink modes, not a casual implementation detail"]
    A6["Material participation evidence:<br/>the archive cutover lane only closed green after probe-to-sink continuity closure under the run-scoped archive prefix, and later richer RTDL proof notes still recorded the archive writer as green while diagnosing other components"]
    A7["A-level meaning:<br/>runtime event history becomes durable, run-scoped archive truth instead of leaving later replay and audit to infer history from scattered remnants"]
  end

